definitions: person who delivers sermons or religious teachings in a church or public setting
examples: The preacher delivered an inspiring sermon about compassion
A traveling preacher visited small towns throughout the region

definitions: act of delivering sermons or religious messages to educate and inspire people
examples: His passionate preaching attracted large crowds every Sunday
The preaching focused on themes of hope and redemption

definitions: opening section of a document that explains its purpose or underlying principles
examples: The preamble outlined the goals of the constitution
She wrote a brief preamble before presenting her proposal

definitions: action taken in advance to prevent something dangerous or unpleasant from happening
examples: Taking vitamins is a simple precaution against illness
The company implemented safety precautions for all workers

definitions: condition of being considered more important than something else and therefore coming first
examples: Emergency vehicles take precedence in traffic situations
Family matters took precedence over his work commitments

definitions: earlier event or action that serves as an example or guide for similar situations
examples: The court ruling set an important legal precedent
There was no precedent for handling such a crisis

definitions: rule or principle intended to regulate behavior or thought in a particular area
examples: The teacher emphasized the precept of treating others kindly
Ancient precepts still guide modern ethical discussions today

definitions: division of a city for administrative or policing purposes
building that houses a local police station
examples: Voters went to their local precinct to cast ballots
The officers returned to the precinct after their shift
The detective worked at the downtown police precinct
Crime rates varied significantly between different precincts

definitions: very steep rock face or cliff that drops down sharply
examples: The hikers carefully approached the dangerous mountain precipice
She stood at the precipice looking down at the valley

definitions: water that falls from clouds in the form of rain, snow, sleet, or hail
examples: The weather forecast predicted heavy precipitation this weekend
Annual precipitation levels affect local agriculture significantly

definitions: quality of being exact and accurate in details or measurements
examples: The surgeon worked with incredible precision during the operation
Scientific instruments require precision in their calibration process

definitions: condition that must exist or be established before something else can happen
examples: Trust is a precondition for any successful partnership
Meeting the preconditions allowed negotiations to begin properly

definitions: something that comes before and indicates the approach of something or someone else
examples: Dark clouds were precursors to the coming storm
This early invention was a precursor to modern computers

definitions: biological interaction where one organism hunts and feeds on another organism
examples: Predation helps maintain balance in natural ecosystems
The documentary showed predation in the African savanna

definitions: person who held a job or position before the current holder
examples: She inherited several projects from her predecessor
The new CEO praised her predecessor's achievements

definitions: unpleasant or embarrassing situation that is hard to get out of
examples: Finding himself locked out was quite a predicament
The company faced a financial predicament after losing contracts

definitions: part of a sentence that tells what the subject does or is
examples: In grammar class, students learned to identify the predicate
The predicate contains the verb and its modifiers

definitions: quality of being able to be predicted or known in advance based on patterns
examples: The predictability of tides helps sailors plan their journeys
Some people find comfort in daily routine's predictability

definitions: something that helps forecast or indicate what will happen in the future
examples: Education level is often a predictor of income
Weather patterns serve as predictors for agricultural planning

definitions: tendency to like or favor something particular over other options
examples: She had a predilection for classical music over pop
His predilection for spicy food was well known

definitions: liability or tendency to suffer from a particular condition or behave in a certain way
examples: Genetic factors create a predisposition to certain diseases
Her cheerful predisposition made her popular among colleagues

definitions: state of being greater in number or importance than other things
examples: The predominance of technology shapes modern communication patterns
There was a clear predominance of young voters

definitions: fact of surpassing all others in importance, quality, or achievement
examples: The university maintained its preeminence in medical research
Her preeminence in the field was widely acknowledged

definitions: action of preventing something by taking action first or acquiring something in advance
examples: The military strategy relied on preemption of enemy attacks
Television networks use preemption for breaking news coverage

definitions: building or structure manufactured in sections that can be easily assembled on site
examples: The prefab homes were assembled quickly after delivery
Schools used prefab classrooms to handle overflow students

definitions: introduction to a book written by the author explaining its purpose or scope
examples: The author's preface explained her research methodology clearly
He always reads the preface before starting a book

definitions: letter or group of letters added to the beginning of a word to change its meaning
examples: The prefix 'un' changes happy to unhappy
Students learned how prefixes modify word meanings

definitions: period of human history before written records were kept or events were documented
examples: Archaeologists study prehistory through artifacts and fossils
Cave paintings provide glimpses into human prehistory

definitions: preconceived opinion not based on reason or experience, often causing unfair treatment
examples: Education helps combat prejudice against different cultures
The hiring process must be free from prejudice

definitions: action or event that comes before or prepares for something more important
examples: The team conducted preliminary research before the project
Preliminary results showed promise for the new treatment

definitions: action or event serving as an introduction to something more important
examples: The border skirmishes were a prelude to war
The pianist played a beautiful prelude before the concert

definitions: head of government in some countries or states
first in importance, order, or position
examples: The premier announced new economic policies yesterday
The state premier met with federal officials
This is the premier medical facility in the region
She attended the premier business school in the country

definitions: first public performance or showing of a play, film, or musical work
examples: Celebrities attended the movie premiere in Hollywood
The opera's premiere received standing ovations from audiences

definitions: period during which someone serves as premier or prime minister
examples: His premiership lasted for two consecutive terms
Economic reforms marked the beginning of her premiership

definitions: strong feeling that something is about to happen, especially something unpleasant
examples: She had a premonition about the accident
His premonition of danger proved to be accurate

definitions: state of being completely engaged with or worried about something
examples: His preoccupation with work affected his family life
The nation's preoccupation with security increased after the attack

definitions: work done to get ready for something
private school preparing students for college
examples: The chef did all the prep before dinner service
Athletes need proper prep before competing
He attended an expensive prep in New England
The prep had excellent college placement rates

definitions: quality or fact of being greater in number, quantity, or importance
examples: The preponderance of evidence supported the defendant's case
There was a preponderance of female students in the program

definitions: word governing a noun or pronoun expressing relation to another word
examples: Common prepositions include 'on', 'in', and 'under'
The preposition shows the relationship between words

definitions: thing that is required as a prior condition for something else
examples: Basic math is a prerequisite for advanced calculus
Meeting all prerequisites ensures smooth project execution

definitions: right or privilege exclusive to a particular person or group
examples: Hiring decisions were the manager's prerogative
It's your prerogative to change your mind

definitions: educational establishment for children too young for elementary school
examples: The preschool teaches basic skills through play
Parents toured several preschools before choosing one

definitions: period of training and preparation before the start of a sports season
examples: Players reported to preseason training in good shape
The team played several preseason exhibition games

definitions: person who introduces or hosts a television or radio program
examples: The news presenter delivered breaking updates throughout the day
Conference presenters shared their research findings effectively

definitions: action of maintaining something in its original state or good condition
examples: Historic preservation protects important buildings from demolition
Food preservation techniques have evolved over centuries

definitions: person who works to preserve historical buildings, artifacts, or natural environments
examples: The preservationist fought to save the old theater
Environmental preservationists protect endangered habitats

definitions: substance used to preserve food or other materials from decay
examples: Natural preservatives extend the shelf life of foods
The museum used special preservatives on ancient documents

definitions: device designed to keep someone safe, especially from drowning
person who maintains or protects something from harm
examples: All passengers must wear life preservers on boats
The coast guard threw a preserver to the swimmer
She was a dedicated preserver of local traditions
Museum preservers carefully maintain valuable artifacts
